<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<section xml:id="sec-3-1-arguments" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Arguments</title>
  <introduction>
  <p>
    Arguments are so important, they  merit their own chapter. 
    They are the essence of your future proofs, these are your "steps" you long for from your 
    calculus class. 
    </p>
  </introduction>
  <subsection xml:id="subsec-3-1-1-arguments" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>Validness</title>
    
    <p>
      To begin you give the most general form for these <em>steps</em>.
    </p>
<definition xml:id="def-argument">
  <title>Argument</title>
  <idx><h>argument</h></idx>
  
  <statement>
    <p>
      The general form of an <term>argument</term> is:
    </p>
    <tabular halign="center">
      
      <row>
        <cell><m>A</m></cell>
      </row>
     
        
     
      <row  bottom="minor">
        <cell><m>B</m></cell>
        
        
      </row>
    
      <row>
        <cell><m>\therefore C</m></cell>
      </row>
    </tabular>
    <p>
      <m>A</m> and <m>B</m> are the assumptions and <m>C</m> is the conclusion. The symbol <m>\therefore</m> is read
      "therefore."
    </p>
  </statement>
</definition>
<p>
  Arguments are simply propositions listed in an order, so we will need to make sense of this in our logical 
  framework. To do so we have the following definition.
</p>
<definition xml:id="def-valid">
  <title>Valid</title>
  <idx><h>valid</h></idx>
    <idx><h>argument</h><h>valid</h></idx>
  
  <statement>
    <p>
      We will say an argument is <term>valid</term> whenever <me>(A\wedge B)\implies C</me> is a tautology.
    </p>
  </statement>
</definition>

<definition xml:id="def-invalid">
  <title>Invalid</title>
  
  
  <statement>
    <p>
      We will say an argument is <term>invalid</term> whenever <me>(A\wedge B)\implies C</me> is a contradiction.
    </p>
  </statement>
</definition>

<p>
  Recall, what it takes for an implication to be true, that is either the antecedent is false or the consequent is true.
</p>
 <p></p>

  <example xml:id="ex-validness">
  <idx><h>valid</h></idx>
    <idx><h>argument</h><h>valid</h></idx>
    <idx><h>argument</h><h>invalid</h></idx>
    <idx><h>argument</h></idx>
    <p>Here are some examples of valid arguments:</p>
    <tabular halign="right">
      <row>
        <cell>All parabolas are functions of degree 2</cell>
      </row>
      <row bottom="medium">
        <cell>All functions of degree 2 are quadratic</cell>
      </row>
      <row>
        <cell><m>\therefore </m> All parabolas are quadratic</cell>
      </row>
    </tabular>

    <tabular halign="right">
      <row>
        <cell>An apple is purple</cell>
      </row>
      <row bottom="medium">
        <cell>An apple is a fruit</cell>
      </row>
      <row>
        <cell><m>\therefore </m> An apple is purple</cell>
      </row>
    </tabular>

    <tabular halign="right">
      <row>
        <cell>All spiders have 8 legs</cell>
      </row>
      <row bottom="medium">
        <cell>A poodle is a spider</cell>
      </row>
      <row>
        <cell><m>\therefore </m> A poodle has 8 legs</cell>
      </row>
    </tabular>
    
    <p>Here is an example of an invalid argument:</p>

    <tabular halign="right">
      <row>
        <cell>All chickens are animals that eat corn</cell>
      </row>
      <row bottom="medium">
        <cell>All chickens are animals that have wings</cell>
      </row>
      <row>
        <cell><m>\therefore </m> All animals that eat corn have wings</cell>
      </row>
    </tabular>
  </example>
  
  <p>Notice that it is not the truth of the premises that makes an argument valid or invalid, but rather the truth of the conclusion.</p>
    <definition xml:id="def-sound">
    <idx><h>sound</h></idx>
    <idx><h>argument</h><h>sound</h></idx>
      <statement>
        <p>
          We say than an argument is <term>sound</term> when it is valid as well as the premises are true. 
        </p>
      </statement>
    </definition>
    <p>
      In <xref ref="ex-validness"/> the argument about parabolas is sound, yet the third example about spiders is valid it is not sound as poodles are not spiders!
    </p>
</subsection>
